I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to create connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We came of age during a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't that easy to determine.
Without having a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations of our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and each person watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific closed spaces.
Unconsciously, we would die to be part of the universal community surrounding all this.
That's why so many of us watch series like The Office or movies like Presenter Star with obsession, full of short references, like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people knew them.
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
There are too many things to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
We get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We're forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
We enter into parasocial relationships with more caution.
We understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without stepping on others along the way.
Lack of collective consciousness about media has led us to develop a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a tumultuous period, and I'm eager to see where this will lead us.
